The illegal dye Sudan 1 was found in chilli powder used by Premium Foods, leading to a recall of 474 products in Britain and the EU.
The Food Standards Agency is working to remove affected items from shelves and urges consumers to return them for a refund.
The dye, linked to cancer risk, was used in various products like shepherd's pie and Pot Noodle flavors.
The FSA's investigation involves local authorities to determine how the dye entered the food chain.
Other countries like China and Cyprus are also affected by the contamination, prompting bans on tainted products.
